english:
  title: Epitaph for the Tomb of Lord Yong, Retired Chamberlain of the Left of the Ministry of Personnel, Holder of the Silver-Green Rank and Title of Grand Commandant of the Palace
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Looking at the gentlemen and officials of antiquity, in their beginnings none failed to take heed of shame and integrity, warning themselves against overflowing abundance. Yet when they attained wealth and rank in their prime, most grew careless of passing days, complacent in their ignorance of withdrawal. Our Chamberlain was altogether different. At sixty-four, already elevated to the highest councils, with but a few ranks separating him from the three great ministries—why did he not reach that seat? Instead, six years before, he took his leave, seeking to escape excessive favor. Had he not done so, long ago he would have risen to the utmost pinnacle, with much still to spare. Is this not what the Book of Changes means by "knowing advance and retreat, survival and ruin, and never losing the proper way"?

    The Yong family traced its origins to the lush pines of Jincheng, where they held the foremost rank among the great clans. Our lord came from this lineage. His given name was Jayangnim, his courtesy name was Damyeon. His great-grandfather held the title of Inspector of the Crown Prince's Household. His grandfather was Great Teacher to the Crown Prince. His father, a founder of merit enshrined in the ancestral temple, served as Chamberlain of the Gate, Scholar of the Hall of Literary Advancement, and Director of the Ministry of Personnel, posthumously honored as Duke of Respectful Gravity. His mother was the daughter of the court official Zhang, chief of the Imperial Wardrobe.

    In his nature, he embodied harmony and purity—grave in manner, sparing with words. His kindness and trustworthiness moved men's hearts; his clarity and frugality set an example for the realm. These were the gifts heaven bestowed upon him.

    In the time of King Uija, as civil officials grew more influential, our lord, at sixteen, entered into bonds of sworn brotherhood with young nobles. He proposed that two military commanders, Wu Gwangchik and Lee Gwangjeong, be admitted to their circle. The others refused. But our lord spoke forth: "Though we gather in private leisure, it is good to have both civil and martial merit. Why should this not be done? Later you will regret your refusal." All agreed. Soon the Gyeongin Rebellion came, and civil officials were nearly annihilated. Yet all who had sworn friendship with Wu and Lee were spared, for those two generals exerted themselves mightily in their rescue. Thus even in youth, our lord possessed the wisdom to perceive fate's movements.

    As the son of a prime minister, he was appointed Attendant of the Palace Guard Bureau, then advanced to Director of the Great Music Bureau. Soon he was sent out as magistrate of Dragon Ridge County. In administering his district, he understood principle and practice thoroughly, uncovering hidden matters with almost divine perception. His reputation spread throughout the region.

    He rose through successive offices: Censor, Chief of the Imperial Wardrobe, Grand Censor, Commissioner of the Ministry of Revenue, Censor of Mixed Matters, Vice Minister of the Grand Storehouse—all at the rank of Counselor-in-Chief. Later he served as Minister of the Right of the Ministry of Personnel at the rank of Grand Commandant. These were the offices he held.

    When sent to inspect the southeast or command the northeast, his authority was such that all trembled. Yet he tempered his rule with kindness and trust, so the people found ease under him. This is why his missions earned him lasting praise.

    Though the rank of third-degree official opened the way to the premiership, when our lord served as Director of the Grand Storehouse, he instead earnestly requested a provincial post, going out as Prefect of the Southern Capital. Thus did he guard against satiety.

    While serving as commissioner of military appointments, a bent pillar in his office hall suddenly straightened of itself—a marvel that spread throughout the realm. This was the effect of his impartial justice, which moved even the spirits.

    When he commanded the east, he paid reverence to the Bodhisattva at Naksan Temple. Suddenly two blue birds appeared, bearing flowers that fell upon his robes. Then a handful of seawater rose up and bathed his forehead. The people say that blue birds appear at this place only to those of perfect virtue and complete sincerity. Thus did his profound merit manifest itself.

    In the second year of Sunggyeong, in the year Gyeyu, he submitted his request for retirement with earnest sincerity. The king, unable to refuse, granted him the title of Silver-Green Rank, Chamberlain of the Left of the Ministry of Personnel, and permitted him to retire home.

    He joined with other retired high officials in forming the Elders' Club, where they gathered to drink and find joy together. For seventeen years he enjoyed the leisure of one freed from office, living in peaceful contentment.

    In the year of Gichuk, on the seventh day of the eighth month, he attended the Elders' Club, spent the evening in quiet feast, and returned home. The next day at noon, he read the Eight Precepts. That night he bathed and retired peacefully. When morning came, he called for his attendants to ask the time, and then he gently passed away. He lived to eighty years.

    Before this, there was one who died and returned to life. He said that in that place, he saw temples and pavilions of great majesty. A guardian there told him: "This is where Chamberlain Yong will come." Though such words seem fantastic, consider that our lord's conduct bore no shame. And since his passing was as peaceful as this, the tale cannot be dismissed. Surely he lived in the realm of virtue.

    He married the daughter of Kim Jonjung, and had three sons and two daughters. The eldest became a teacher at the National Academy but died young. The second is now Director of the Palace Guard Bureau, Inspector of the Censorate, Scholar of the Precious Text Hall, and Keeper of the Imperial Decrees. The youngest became an imperial attendant but died before his father. The elder daughter married into a noble house but was widowed young. The younger daughter is now likewise a widow.

    When arranging his burial, the Director of Investigation brought me his biography and requested this epitaph. Receiving it, I wept, saying: "Alas! Here was one of the ancient upright—such a sage and gentleman as him I shall not see again. How could I refuse to write his epitaph?"

    Therefore I inscribe:

    Bright and steadfast minister,
    Beam upon which this realm depends,
    The people's hearts turned toward you—
    Yet you released your place.

    Though that post was not the highest,
    You yourself chose to step back.
    You withdrew, yet men's hearts
    Felt that something was missing.

    Gray hairs and long life,
    These you did not seek.
    Yet heaven, seeing your sincerity,
    Bestowed them nonetheless.

    Your upright heart moved the spirits—
    The crooked pillar straightened,
    The blue birds came to visit.
    For you, such things were ordinary;
    For others, miracles.

    Alas, the ancient virtuous have passed away,
    Where now shall the world find its model?

    There stands a mountain, high and steep,
    Where waters flow around its base.
    This is where the lord now rests,
    Where auspicious peace abides.

    Upon stone engraved and sealed in earth,
    Your light will shine through ten thousand generations.
  footnotes:
    - 'The Blue Birds: A reference to a folk belief that blue birds were divine messengers appearing only to those of exceptional virtue. This detail, combined with the straightening pillar, emphasizes the supernatural confirmation of the lord''s moral character.'
    - 'The Elders'' Club (耆老會): A social gathering of retired high officials, reflecting a Confucian ideal of honorable withdrawal from office to pursue cultivation and leisure.'
    - 'The Eight Precepts: Buddhist moral precepts, suggesting the lord''s personal piety and spiritual preparation for death.'
    - 'The Gyeongin Rebellion: A reference to a historical uprising during the reign of King Uija of Baekje (義王, r. 1455-1468), though the dating in the text suggests King Injong''s reign (1122-1146).'
